From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ci <ci@local>
Date: 2026-05-21T07:10:58Z
Subject: [PATCH] patches/0042-fman-pcd-kg-graft-cc.patch

PR14z13 (2026-05-21): graft an ASK CC tree onto an existing kernel-owned
KG scheme instead of allocating a NEW scheme that loses the FMan KG
dispatch race against the in-tree default.

Background
----------
At MAC bringup, dpaa_eth.c calls keygen_port_hashing_init() for every
probed FMan MAC.  That helper uses get_free_scheme_id() which is
first-fit from slot 0 -> on LS1046A the 5 probed MACs (eth0..eth4)
land in KG scheme slots 0..4 with match_vector=0 (catch-all hash
distribution to per-CPU RX FQs).

ASK's prior fman_pcd_kg_scheme_create() PR14z5 path then allocated
NEW schemes at slot 5/6 (FWD/REV pipelines), bound them to the same
hwports (0x10/0x11) as the in-tree defaults, and attached its CC tree
via fman_pcd_kg_attach_cc().  Live silicon regdump on 2026-05-21
confirmed the schemes are correctly programmed (kgse_mv=0x001c0006
specific 5-tuple, kgse_ccbs=0x0005ac00/0x0005c200 valid CC handles,
fmkg_pe_sp bits 26/25 = scheme IDs 5/6 via the 31-N reverse encoding
in keygen_bind_port_to_schemes()).

BUT the FMan v3 KG silicon dispatches EXACTLY ONE scheme per packet:
the lowest scheme ID set in fmkg_pe_sp for the port wins.  Scheme 3
(in-tree, kgse_mv=0, bound to 0x10) consumes every frame BEFORE
scheme 5 (ASK) gets a look.  Measured kgse_spc: scheme 3 = 63,160,848
during a 6.98 Gbps iperf3 -P 8 burst; scheme 5 = 0.

Result: HW offload is fully inert; the 7 Gbps stream rides the kernel
SW fast path consuming ~45-60% softirq CPU (M2 acceptance gate FAIL).

Architectural fix
-----------------
Option A from the PR14z13 decision matrix: ASK does NOT create new
KG schemes.  Instead, ASK GRAFTS its CC tree onto the EXISTING
kernel-owned scheme via KGSE_CCBS programming.  The kernel scheme's
parser/extract recipe stays unchanged; KGSE_CCBS is updated to point
at ASK's CC tree.  The CC tree's miss-action falls back to the
kernel scheme's original base_fqid, preserving kernel control-plane
RX (ARP, SYN, ICMP) and VPP AF_XDP consumption via per-CPU FQs.

This pattern is the strategic precedent for all future ASK2 features
(NAT44, VLAN push/pop, IPsec offload via CAAM) and aligns with VPP's
"layer on top, don't displace" philosophy:

  kernel owns scheme identity -> ASK extends via CC -> VPP layers via AF_XDP
                          ^                    ^                    ^
                          |                    |                    |
                      dpaa_eth.c          fman_pcd_kg_graft_cc   fsl_dpa+AF_XDP

This patch
----------
Adds three new public API entry points:

  fman_pcd_kg_lookup_port_scheme(pcd, port_id, *scheme_id, *base_fqid)
    Reads fmkg_pe_sp[port_id] via AR-mediated indirect access, returns
    the LOWEST scheme ID bound to that hwport (which is the one FMan
    KG will actually dispatch to per packet) and that scheme's
    KGSE_FQB base_fqid (so CC miss can fall back to it).  Returns
    -ENOENT if no scheme is bound to the port.

  fman_pcd_kg_graft_cc(pcd, scheme_id, cc_tree)
    AR-mediated read-modify-write on KGSE_CCBS of the named scheme,
    setting it to cc_tree's group_table_off (same encoding as the
    existing fman_pcd_kg_attach_cc() applies to ASK-owned schemes).
    The scheme MUST already be in 'used' state -- this helper does
    not allocate.  Returns 0 on success.

  fman_pcd_kg_ungraft_cc(pcd, scheme_id)
    Symmetric inverse: AR-mediated RMW that clears KGSE_CCBS back to
    0, restoring the scheme's pre-graft "scheme dispatches directly
    to hash-FQ" behaviour.  Called from ask.ko on module unload.

Implementation reuses the existing keygen_scheme_set_ccbs() primitive
landed by PR14c-body-4 (patch 0012), which already does the correct
AR-mediated RMW preserving every other KGSE_* field of the target
scheme.  The new helper keygen_lookup_port_scheme() in fman_keygen.c
adds a parallel AR-mediated read of fmkg_pe.fmkg_pe_sp via the
SEL_PORT_ENTRY indirect window.

Locking model unchanged: all three new entry points take pcd->lock
via fman_pcd_get_lock() before touching keygen state.

What this patch does NOT do
---------------------------
- Does NOT modify ask.ko.  The ASK-side rewrite of
  ask_hw_port_bind() to call fman_pcd_kg_graft_cc() instead of
  fman_pcd_kg_scheme_create()+bind+attach is a separate change in
  kernel/flavors/ask/oot-modules/ask/ask_hw.c (PR14z13-ask, lands
  next session).
- Does NOT change CC tree miss-action semantics.  The CC tree's
  miss_action.type = FMAN_PCD_ACTION_FORWARD_FQ with next_fqid =
  <kernel scheme's base_fqid> is set by the ASK side using the
  base_fqid returned by lookup_port_scheme().
- Does NOT touch dpaa_eth.c.  Kernel-owned scheme allocation policy
  is preserved verbatim; ASK simply grafts onto whatever the kernel
  already allocated.

Verification
------------
1. patch-health.sh --flavor ask --source release: must not regress.
2. KUnit (lands in PR14z13-kunit): graft_unbound_scheme_returns_einval,
   graft_then_ungraft_restores_kgse_ccbs_zero,
   lookup_port_scheme_returns_lowest_bound.
3. On hardware after the ASK side lands:
   - bin/ask-pcd-regdump.py shows kgse_ccbs != 0 on the kernel scheme
     (slot 3 or 4) after ask.ko load + first iperf3 burst.
   - kgse_spc on the kernel scheme keeps incrementing (proves frames
     are still walking the parser).
   - kgse_spc on the ASK-created scheme slots (5/6) stays 0 because
     ASK no longer creates them.
   - eth3 rx_dropped stops growing and matches eth4 tx_packets minus
     ACK overhead (proves CC tree is consuming the 5-tuple matches
     and forwarding via silicon to peer TX FQ).
   - bin/verify-ask-flow-offload.sh CPU metric drops from ~45-60% to
     <=5% (M2 acceptance gate PASS).
